body:
Hi, I have noticed that Icarus seems to finish the current simulation cycle instead of exiting immediately after a call to `$finish`. E.g., consider the following module illustrating this:

```systemverilog
module test;

logic x = 1;

initial begin
 $monitor("monitor: ", x);
 $finish(x);
end

initial x = 0;

// still happens with the following variants:
//
// initial x <= 0;
// initial #0 x = 0;
// initial x = #0 0;
//
// but not with longer delays:
//
// initial #1 x = 0;
// initial x = #1 0;

initial $display("display: ", x);

endmodule
```

The output from running the above is:

```
> iverilog test.sv && ./a.out
test.sv:7: $finish(1) called at 0 (1s)
display: 0
monitor: 0
```

The standard just says the following about `$finish`:

> The `$finish` system task causes the simulator to exit and pass control back to the host operating system.

It seems that at least the four commercial simulators on EDA Playground interpret this as "exit immediately" rather than "finish the current simulation cycle and then finish".

Since the standard does not say much it is open to interpretation, but is it possible that "exit immediately" is a more convincing read than "finish what you are doing and then exit"?

E.g., with the "finish what you are doing and then exit" interpretation, we can have long/infinite executions after a `$finish$` call and delay the exit/never actually exit:

```systemverilog
module test2;

initial $finish;

initial forever;

endmodule
```

